			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Kiting on raids<a name="51577"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 13 04 2:41 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I've done this where we ran out and I've done it where we MGB'd after, both seem to work just fine, the trick with running out is you generally want to do that with a raiding force you know and trust to do it right.  AEing the butterflies seems to work best, they do go down pretty fast and I've kited the gargoyles before, I've also had rangers do it.  Most raids I do include a couple of rangers who are great at kiting mobs like this.
<br />

<br />
Kiting makes LMM go a lot smoother too, instead of killing his guards and having them respawn during the fight you have a designated kiter, who can handle the long arduous task, pull the guards from his room and kite them out and around the fountain for the entire fight.  
<br />

<br />
Your main question I gathered though, was how do you keep agro.. and that is not an easy task sometimes, it's the reason I don't like being asked to tank ldon's and such.  I generally use mezzes to pull agro, a failed Mezz attempt seems to generate a tone of agro, so does Harmony of Sound.. now if someone pulls agro from you with a cheal or something like that you'll have a helluva a time getting it back, the trick is to grab the mob early and keep it on the outer walls, the gargs you kite as close to the walls as possible and make sure your raid knows to stay near the center of the room.  Aggro control is not a one man job, takes some team work.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><img src="http://www.geetronics.com/liis4.jpg"><hr>
